03886nam a22005535i 9780822393771DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223937717 a10.1515/97808223937712doi  a(DE-B1597)552130  a(OCoLC)1202623698  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHF5827.9b.A25 2012 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a659.101/92231 aAcland, Charles R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSwift Viewing :bThe Popular Life of Subliminal Influence /cCharles R. Acland. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (322 p.) :b58 illustrations, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue Black Magic on Mars -- tOne Subliminal Communication as Vernacular Media Critique -- tTwo Mind, Media, and Remote Control -- tThree The Swift View -- tFour Mind- Probing Admen -- tFive Crossing the Popular Threshold -- tSix The Hidden and the Overload -- tSeven From Mass Brainwashing to Rapid Mass Learning -- tEight Textual Strategies for Media Saturation -- tNine Critical Reasoning in a Cluttered Age -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the late 1950s, the idea that hidden, imperceptible messages could influence mass behavior has been debated, feared, and ridiculed. In Swift Viewing, Charles R. Acland reveals the secret story of subliminal influence, showing how an obscure concept from experimental psychology became a mainstream belief about our vulnerability to manipulation in an age of media clutter. He chronicles the enduring popularity of the dubious claims about subliminal influence, tracking their migration from nineteenth-century hypnotism to twentieth-century front-page news. His expansive history of popular concern about subliminal messages shows how the notion of "hidden persuaders" became a vernacular media critique, one reflecting anxiety about a rapidly expanding media environment. Through a deep archive of eclectic examples, including educational technology in the American classroom, mind-control tropes in science fiction, Marshall McLuhan's media theories, and sensational claims in the late 1950s about subliminal advertising, Acland establishes the subliminal as both a product of and a balm for information overload.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSubliminal advertisingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393771zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393771.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles